Use the pandas dataframe.groupby() function to group by county name. .sort_values() quickly sorts by selected grouping parameter.

Defining a function enables printing the n most common county names:

In [ ]:
def countyFrequency (n):
    groupDf = gdf.groupby(by="NAME").count().sort_values('GEO_ID', ascending=False)
    print("The {} most common county names are:".format(n))
    for i in range(n):
        print(groupDf.index[i])
        
countyFrequency(5)

The 5 most common county names are:
Washington
Jefferson
Franklin
Jackson
Lincoln

Task 2: Derive summary statistics for states, for example, number of counties, counties with max/min area

Combining dataframe.groupby() with pd.NamedAgg() produces columns with user-specified columns and aggregation methods:

In [ ]:
stateDF = gdf.groupby(by='STATE').agg(
    nCounties = pd.NamedAgg(column='GEO_ID', aggfunc='count'),
    maxCountyArea = pd.NamedAgg(column = 'CENSUSAREA', aggfunc='max'),
    minCountyArea = pd.NamedAgg(column = 'CENSUSAREA', aggfunc='min'),
    totalCountyArea = pd.NamedAgg(column = 'CENSUSAREA', aggfunc='sum'),
    avgCountyArea = pd.NamedAgg(column = 'CENSUSAREA', aggfunc='mean')    
)
stateDF.reset_index(inplace=True)
stateDF = stateDF.rename(columns = {'index':'new column name'})

Task 3: Join fips code to get full names of states (plesae do a real join using merge)

In [ ]:
# Load JSON files
with open("stateCodeToFips.json", 'r') as a, open("fipsToState.json", 'r') as b:
    codeToFips = json.load(a)
    fipsToState = json.load(b)

# pd.melt transposes the dataframe   
codeToFips = pd.DataFrame([codeToFips])
codeToFips = pd.melt(codeToFips)

fipsToState = pd.DataFrame([fipsToState])
fipsToState = pd.melt(fipsToState)

Left merges preserve the structure of the county geoDataFrame:

In [ ]:
countiesUpdate = pd.merge(gdf, fipsToState,
                            how = 'left',
                            left_on='STATE',
                            right_on='variable')

countiesUpdate = pd.merge(countiesUpdate, codeToFips, 
                            how='left',
                            left_on='STATE',
                            right_on='value')

countiesUpdate = (countiesUpdate.drop(['variable_x', 'value_y'], axis=1).rename(columns={'value_x':'STATENAME',

Task 4: Plot maps to show all the counties with the most common names from first task

Using similar logic as above creates a list of n most common county names. The county geoDataFrame is queried to subset rows with county names in the generated list. After defining a CRS, a map of all counties with n most common names is produced using geoDataFrame.explore():

In [ ]:
def mapCountyFrequency(n):
    frequencyDF = countiesUpdate.groupby(by="NAME").count().sort_values('GEO_ID', ascending=False)
    countyList = frequencyDF.head(n).index.tolist()
    subDF = countiesUpdate.query('NAME in @countyList')
    countyMap = subDF.set_crs(4326).explore(column = 'NAME')
    return countyMap

mapCountyFrequency(10)
